GET info about SpaceX launchpads

GET info about SpaceX launchpads

get_SpaceX_launchpads(name = NULL)

Arguments

name

character: Name of lauchnpads. Choose "ksc_lc_39a" or NULL. By default all three rocket data are returned.

Value

data.frame with parsed data from SpaceX API.

Examples


## get details about all launchpads
get_SpaceX_launchpads()

#> 2                                                                                                                                                                                                                               SpaceX new launch site currently under construction to help keep up with the Falcon 9 and Heavy manifests. Expected to be completed in late 2018. Initially will be limited to 12 flights per year, and only GTO launches.

Expected to first be used during the Formosat-5 launch.

After SLC-40 repairs are complete, it will be upgraded to support Falcon Heavy, a process which will take about two months. In the future it will launch commercial crew missions and the Interplanetary Transport System.
#> 7                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   SpaceX original west coast launch pad for Falcon 1. Performed a static fire but was never used for a launch and abandoned due to scheduling conflicts.
#> 8                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     SpaceX primary west coast launch pad for polar orbits and sun synchronous orbits, primarily used for Iridium. Also intended to be capable of launching Falcon Heavy.

## get details about launchpad "ksc_lc_39a"
get_SpaceX_launchpads("ksc_lc_39a")
